**• 4\. Loops and conditions:**   
—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
While statements take this form:

    while (condition) {  
      // code block to be executed  
    }

While can also use 'break' and 'continue' to break out of the loop or to continue to the next iteration \- much like python.

—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
Do while statements look like this:

    do {  
      // code here  
    }  
    while (condition);

—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
The for loop syntax looks like this:

    for (x=start; x=end; how to increment) {  
      // code here  
    }

—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
In C we can use if, else, else if with if statements.

    if (condition1) {

    // block of code to be executed if condition1 is true  
    } else if (condition2) {  
    // block of code to be executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is true  
    } else {  
      // block of code to be executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is false

    }

—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
If statements can have a shorthand which looks like this:

    variable \= (condition) ? expressionTrue : expressionFalse;

—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**• 5\. Derived datatypes:**   
	Main focus:

* Voids

The void is a datatype which is used when a variable is empty and therefore has no type.

* Arrays

Arrays simply store many variables. They can store different datatypes but not together e.g.   
you could have an int array or a float array but they should be made of all ints or all floats.

Arrays are defined with square brackets.

    int myIntArray\[\] \= {0,1,2,3}  
      
    float myFloatArray\[\] \= {0.01, 0, 0.3}

We can also leave them empty originally and just define their size.  
\-  A multi-dimensional 2D array is written like this:

dataType arrayName \[rows\]\[columns\];  
—----------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
\#include \<stdio.h\>

int main() {

    int rows \= 2;  
    int columns \= 3;

    float arrayName \[rows\]\[columns\];  
—----------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
}

* Functions (and using recursion in function)

In C the syntax for creating a function looks like this;

    void myFunction(comma separated parameters with their datatype) {  
      // code here  
    }  
      
If void is used as above then it means that the function you are creating does not have a value which it returns. 

Functions can be created outside of main and then stored up for future use
